TARGET LEAF SPOT, CUCUMBER - KOREA, SOUTH
*****************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: 20 Jan 2003
From: ProMED-mail<promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Brit Soc Plant Pathol, NEW DISEASE REPORTS, Vol. 6 [edited]

Occurrence of target leaf spot disease caused by _Corynespora cassicola_
on cucumber in Korea

MK Kwon, BR Kang, BH Cho and YC Kim <yckimyc@chonnam.ac.kr> Applied Plant
Science Division and Agricultural Plant Stress Research Center, College of
Agriculture and Life Sciences, Chonnam National University, Gwangju
500-757, Korea. Accepted for publication 13 Jan 2003

This is the first report of target leaf spot of cucumber (_Cucumis
sativus_) grown in open fields, caused by _Corynespora cassicola_, in
Chonnam province of Korea. A similar disease caused by _Corynespora
melonis_[Cc] was observed in 1991 in greenhouse-cultivated cucumber in the
Jinju area of Korea (Kang et al., 1993).

Surveys of commercial fields between 2000 and 2001 in Chonnam province,
revealed severe damage on the Japanese cucumber variety, Baeksung 3, but
not on Korean varieties. By 2002 these varieties were severely affected by
target leaf spot in fields in Chonnam and Gyeongnam provinces.

Leaf symptoms began as small brown spots with yellow halos, enlarging and
becoming irregularly shaped before defoliation occurred. The morphology of
the fungus consistently obtained from these infected spots matched the
description of Cc (Ellis & Holliday, 1971). Conidiophores were erect and
simple, pale to mid-brown, 205-725 micrometers long, and 5-8 micrometers
wide. Conidia were formed singly or in chains, obclavate to cylindrical,
straight or curved, subhyaline to pale olivaceous-brown, 22-300 micrometers
long and 5-10 micrometers wide at the base, with 7 - 11 pseudosepta.

Identical 610-bp PCR products were obtained using primers to amplify
internal transcribed spacers (ITS) of the 18S rRNA regions from the new
Korean isolates and a reference strain ATCC64204 of Cc (Wyszogrodzka et
al., 1987).

A conidial suspension (10 000 conidia per ml) of Cc was prepared from
3-week-old cultures grown on PDA and sprayed on cucumber plants with
completely developed third leaves. After incubation in a dew chamber for 24
hours at 30 deg C, plants were maintained at 25 deg C. Small brown spots
appeared on leaves within 3 days. Leaves of water-sprayed control plants
remained healthy.

Cc was re-isolated from leaf lesions and was identical morphologically to
the original Cc isolate sprayed on test plants. Greenhouse studies
indicated that a long dew period and high temperatures (25-30 deg C)
increase disease severity.

An isolate of Cc has been deposited in the Korean Agricultural Culture
Collection (KACC40941).

References

Ellis MB, Holliday P, 1971. _Corynespora cassicola_. C.M.I. Descriptions
of Pathogenic Fungi and Bacteria, No 303. Kew, UK: CAB International
Mycological Institute.

Kang SW, Kwon JH, Chung BK, Cho JK, Lee YS, Kim HK, 1993. Identification
and etiological of new disease, Corynespora leaf spot of cucumber caused by
_Corynespora melonis_ (Cook) Lindaw green house cultivation in Korea. RDA
Journal of Agricultural Science 35, 332-336.

Wyszogrodzka AJ, 1987. Multiple-pathogen inoculation of cucumber (_Cucumis
sativus_) seedlings. Plant Disease 71, 275-280.

