<promed@promedmail.org>

[Cc has a wide natural host range, including tomato and papaya. It may
survive up to 2 years in crop debris, thus providing inoculum for continued
spread. Cc strains from different hosts have been found often but are not
always able to cross-infect other hosts. It is seedborne in soybean, but
little is known about its survival in seeds of other crops. The primary
means of field spread is by wind-blown conidia. Greatest disease severity
from Cc appears to occur in seasonal periods when the temperature is
approximately 28 deg C. Plant resistance has been used to control target
spot in European cucumber crops for many years. Resistance to Cc has also
been documented in soybean and tomato. The disease is controlled primarily
by periodic applications of protectant fungicides.

Additional reference:
<http://edis.ifas.ufl.edu/VH052>

This document is PP-39, a series of the Plant Pathology Department, Florida
Cooperative Extension Service, Institute of Food and Agricultural Sciences,
University of Florida. Reviewed: December 1993. - Mod.DH]
